04160nam a22005655i 9780773588219DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735882197 a10.1515/97807735882192doi  a(DE-B1597)655910  a(OCoLC)828850243  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA412.5.C2bD83 2013eb 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a362.10971qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aDuckett, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCanadian Medicare :bWe Need It and We Can Keep It /cStephen Duckett, Adrian Peetoom. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (184 p.) :b15 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tA Call to Action -- tOur Medicare Structure in Broad Strokes -- tIs Medicare Sustainable? -- tMedicare and Not Much Else? -- tLet’s Get Healthier -- tPrimary Care: The Foundation -- tPharmacare: The Time is Right -- tInnovations in Health Care: Who Benefits? -- tThose Seniors Once More -- tHospitals: Quality, Access, and Efficiency -- tNurturing and Obtaining the Right Skills -- tMedicare Voices -- tThe Road Ahead -- tRecommendations -- tKey Canadian Health Organizations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMedicare has been a crucial part of Canadian identity for nearly fifty years, and it stands in marked contrast to the US health system. But these facts alone do not protect it from dismissive swipes and criticisms, claims that the system is unsustainable, and even proposals to change medicare's fundamentals. In Canadian Medicare, Stephen Duckett and Adrian Peetoom show that the shared values underpinning medicare still provide a sound basis for the system's design. While medicare remains an important pillar of Canadian policy, changes can and must be made. The authors argue for improved primary care to better address increases in chronic diseases, a comprehensive strategy to provide care for the elderly, and the introduction of pharmacare. They demonstrate how, with proper investment, the health of Canadians can be maintained and even enhanced while the nation remains financially responsible. Accessibly written and clearly presented, Canadian Medicare is a call for Canadian citizens to improve on the foundation built by Tommy Douglas and Lester B. Pearson, to become more knowledgeable about their health care, and to let their politicians know that they need to act.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHealth care reformxCanadaxCanada. 0aHealth care reformzCanada. 0aNational health insurancexCanada. 0aNational health insurancezCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aPeetoom, Adrian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358821940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588219/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles